{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477762"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14714"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14714"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.41,0.01,0.54,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7407"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43599"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"486"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44220"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent after noticing dark-coloured urine for two days. He has had a sore throat and runny nose for the past four days. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His throat is erythematous with enlarged tonsils. Urinalysis shows 3+ blood and 1+ protein.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute interstitial nephritis","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","Alport syndrome","IgA nephropathy","Thin basement membrane disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of IgA nephropathy: macroscopic haematuria occurring simultaneously with an upper respiratory tract infection (synpharyngitic haematuria). \u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common form of glomerulonephritis worldwide and typically presents in children and young adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-streptococcal glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly but typically occurs 1-2 weeks after a streptococcal infection (post-infectious), not during the infection. It also usually presents with more systemic features including hypertension and oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThin basement membrane disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause persistent microscopic haematuria but rarely causes episodes of macroscopic haematuria. It is an inherited condition that usually presents in childhood with isolated microscopic haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlport syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited condition that causes progressive kidney disease with haematuria, but it typically presents with persistent microscopic haematuria and associated features such as hearing loss and eye abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute interstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute kidney injury, often in association with medication use (particularly antibiotics or NSAIDs). While it can cause haematuria, the timing with upper respiratory tract infection is more suggestive of IgA nephropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe definitive diagnosis of IgA nephropathy requires a kidney biopsy showing mesangial IgA deposits. However, in a patient with typical presentation and mild disease (normal blood pressure, minimal proteinuria), observation with regular monitoring may be appropriate initially.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["IgA nephropathy commonly presents with macroscopic haematuria coinciding with upper respiratory tract infections (synpharyngitic haematuria).","The presence of proteinuria and hypertension in IgA nephropathy indicates more severe disease.","Renal biopsy showing mesangial IgA deposits is required for definitive diagnosis of IgA nephropathy."],"references":["Habas E, Ali E, Farfar K, Errayes M, Alfitori J, Habas E, Ghazouani H, Akbar R, Khan F, Al Dab A, Elzouki AN. IgA nephropathy pathogenesis and therapy: Review \u0026 updates. Medicine (Baltimore). 2022 Dec 2;101(48):e31219. doi: 10.1097/MD.0000000000031219. PMID: 36482575; PMCID: PMC9726424."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43599"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14714"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43599"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T14:20:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T14:20:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7407"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synony